title: Complement or substitute? How AI increases the demand for human skills

sections.text:
#### Abstract

This paper examines whether artificial intelligence (AI) acts as a substitute or complement to human labour, drawing on 12 million online job vacancies from the United States spanning 2018-2023. We adopt a two-pronged approach: first, analysing "internal effects" within roles explicitly requiring AI, and second, investigating "external effects" that arise when industries, occupations, and regions experience increases in AI demand. Our focus centres on whether complementary skills-such as digital literacy, teamwork, resilience, agility, or analytical thinking-become more prevalent and valuable as AI adoption grows. Results show that AI-focused roles are nearly twice as likely to require skills like resilience, agility, or analytical thinking compared to non-AI roles. Furthermore, these skills command a significant wage premium; data scientists, for instance, are offered $5-10 \%$ higher salaries if they also possess resilience or ethics capabilities. We observe positive spillover effects: a doubling of AI-specific demand across industries correlates with a $5 \%$ increase in demand for complementary skills, even outside AI-related roles. Conversely, tasks vulnerable to AI substitution, such as basic data skills or translation, exhibit modest declines in demand. However, the external effect is clearly net positive: Complementary effects are up to 1.7 x larger than substitution effects. These results are consistent across economies, including the United Kingdom and Australia. Our findings highlight the necessity of reskilling workers in areas where human expertise remains increasingly valuable and ensuring workers can effectively complement and leverage emerging AI technologies.


Keywords: AI, Automation, Complementarity, Future of Work, Labour Markets, Skills JEL Class: C55, J21, J23, J24, J31

# Introduction 

Does technology diminish or strengthen the role of humans in the world of work? We ask this question as recent technological advancements and their adoption have significant implications for labour markets (e.g., Acemoglu et al., 2021; Acemoglu \& Autor, 2011; Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2020b; Autor et al., 2003; Bessen, 2019; Brynjolfsson \& McAfee, 2014; Frank et al., 2019). Much prior work has focused on automation potential, offering substantial evidence for the use of artificial intelligence (AI) in substituting routine cognitive and manual skills (e.g., Autor et al., 2003; Autor \& Dorn, 2013). More recent evidence suggests these effects now extend to non-routine cognitive tasks that were traditionally the domain of highly educated and highly paid workers (Boussioux et al., 2024; Geerling et al., 2023; Girotra et al., 2023; Kung et al., 2023). Conversely, a smaller body of literature documents augmentation effects such as improved productivity or efficiency in analytical, programming, or writing tasks (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2020b; Dell'Acqua et al., 2023; Eloundou et al., 2023; Noy \& Zhang, 2023), alongside new complementation effects, namely higher demand or valuation for certain skills used in tandem with AI (Alekseeva et al., 2021; Stephany \& Teutloff, 2024). In sum, there remains little consensus on precisely which skills AI systems excel at, and thus little consensus on the specific labour market outcomes they might produce (Brynjolfsson \& Mitchell, 2017). This research seeks to clarify the nature of AI-driven labour market effects-particularly these less-understood complementation effects-and to illuminate how and where such changes occur.

In order to balance the benefits and concerns associated with "AI at work" (Brynjolfsson et al., 2023), researchers, policymakers, employers, and job-seekers alike require robust empirical insights into these issues. To date, however, much prior work has relied on speculative forecasting (e.g., Agrawal et al., 2019; Webb, 2019) or on expert opinion and theoretical models, which may rest on assumptions that are neither validated nor universally accepted (Yilmaz et al., 2023). This limitation restricts the practical applicability of such work for policymakers seeking to inform labour market policy, employers engaging in strategic workforce planning, and job-seekers aiming to enhance their prospects. Moreover, given the very recent surge in AI adoption (McKinsey, 2023; World Economic Forum, 2023), there have so far been

"substantially fewer" studies examining AI (Brynjolfsson et al., 2023: 4) compared with investigations into other technologies. Building on research linking technology adoption to shifts in skills demand (e.g., Acemoglu et al., 2021) and in line with skill-biased technological change theory, we posit that artificial intelligence may both substitute and complement certain skills.

Gathering empirical evidence on technology's labour market impacts is challenging (Frank et al., 2019). Following Acemoglu et al. (2021) and Deming and Noray (2020), we assume that changes in skills demand and valuation are observable through job vacancy postings, as employers signal their evolving requirements and willingness to pay for specific skills. This study therefore leverages a dataset of approximately 12 million $(\mathrm{n}=11,729,662)$ online job vacancy postings from the United States, covering January 2018 to December 2023. Scraped from more than 65,000 websites-including national and local job boards, corporate career sites, and job vacancy aggregators (Lightcast Data, n.d.)-these postings represent the "near-universe" of online vacancies (Acemoglu et al., 2021, p.1). In the pages that follow, we address a key question for economists and policymakers alike: whether AI technologies are leading to substitution (i.e., reducing work) or complementation (i.e., increasing demand for particular types of work).

Turning to our findings, we first show that demand for AI roles in our dataset has risen more steeply than overall labour demand. Next, we reveal a substantial increase in the demand for skills seen as complementary to AI—such as digital literacy, teamwork, and resilience and agility-along with a growing wage premium for these skills within AI-focused roles, for example among data scientists. Conversely, skills considered more easily substituted by AI, such as customer service, summarisation, and text review, have declined in both popularity and value within AI-related positions. We then delve deeper into complementary skills, demonstrating that demand and wage premiums are particularly pronounced for some of these, and that specific combinations of AI and complementary skills appear especially popular and profitable. We illustrate these compounding effects with examples of AI roles, such as data scientists.

In the second half of the paper, we expand our analysis to examine external effects across the broader economy, establishing that AI shapes both complementary

and substitute skills even in roles not directly related to AI. We find statistically significant external effects at occupation, industry, and regional levels. Specifically, growth in AI roles is associated with an uptick in demand for non-AI complementary roles and a decline in demand for non-AI substitutable roles. Crucially, the evidence indicates that the complementarity effect is considerably stronger than the substitution effect. We replicate this analysis for the United Kingdom and Australia, confirming the robustness of our findings. Finally, we conclude by discussing the broader implications for policymakers, employers, and job-seekers.

# Literature Review
## Technological Change and Labour Market Evolution

Whether AI complements or substitutes human labour is a core debate in the literature. Technological change has repeatedly reshaped labour markets, from the mechanisation of the Industrial Revolution to today's digital transformations, each redefining workforce skills and economic landscapes (Frey, 2019; Goldin \& Katz, 2007b; Schwab, 2017). During the Industrial Revolution, production methods modernised and manufacturing jobs emerged, triggering urbanisation, population growth, and a reconfiguration of economic structures (Stearns, 2020). In the 20th century, scientific progress, electrification, and automation accelerated mass production, especially in manufacturing, where robotics replaced human labour in some routine tasks ( Xu et al., 2018). At the same time, the service sector expanded, generating new employment opportunities (Urquhart, 1984). These shifts reflect how technology can simultaneously destroy certain types of jobs while creating others.

The "Information Age" (Castells, 1997; Heeks, 1999), powered by semiconductors and computing (Bresnahan \& Trajtenberg, 1995), made information technology a core driver of productivity, innovation, and competitiveness (Castells, 1997). More recently, the "fourth industrial revolution" has seen AI, increasing computing power, and cyber-physical systems (e.g., IoT) reshape labour markets (Autor et al., 1998; Schwab, 2017). Research shows that while these technologies can enhance productivity (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2020b) or redirect workers to more meaningful tasks (Parmer, 2023), concerns remain about negative effects such as wage inequality (Autor et al., 1998; Krueger, 1993), worker displacement (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2020a; Frey \& Osborne, 2017), and labour market polarisation (Brynjolfsson \& McAfee, 2014). Though warnings about job loss to new technologies regularly recur (Stephany \& Teutloff, 2024), there is increasing urgency to understand how ongoing AI advancements affect employment and wages (McKinsey, 2023; World Economic Forum, 2023).

# Understanding AI's Impact on Skills and Work 

Studies specifically examining AI's labour market effects on skills remain relatively few (Acemoglu et al., 2021; Brynjolfsson et al., 2023). Notable recent contributions include experimental research demonstrating AI's ability to augment human workers' writing tasks (Noy \& Zhang, 2023) and consultancy-based knowledge work (Dell'Acqua et al., 2023). Other studies point to substitution, such as AI's impact on security analysts' employment and wages (Grennan \& Michaely, 2020) and evidence of AI start-ups automating routine work to reduce labour costs (Bessen et al., 2023). These findings highlight the tension between augmentation and automation and underscore the importance of disentangling these effects.

Debates about whether AI substitutes or complements human work are central to discussions on the future of employment. Early occupation-based research (e.g., Bessen, 2016) helped spark interest in technology's impact on jobs but was criticised for treating occupations as homogeneous (Frank et al., 2019). A subsequent task-based approach (e.g., Arntz et al., 2016; Autor et al., 2003; Autor \& Handel, 2013) showed how specific tasks-such as formal reasoning-within certain professional and technical roles (Acemoglu \& Autor, 2011) can be automated or augmented. Finally, the skills-based approach (e.g., Acemoglu \& Autor, 2011) posits that the degree to which a role is automatable or augmentable depends on its skill composition, recognising that occupations are best seen as bundles of skills (Frank et al., 2019; Stephany \& Teutloff, 2024).

## Substitution, Augmentation, and Skill Complementarities in the AI Era

Substantial evidence supports AI's capacity to automate routine manual and cognitive tasks (Autor et al., 2003; Autor \& Dorn, 2013). More recent work suggests this extends to non-routine cognitive activities, including problem-solving and creative output once exclusive to highly educated, well-paid workers (Boussioux et al., 2024; Girotra et al., 2023; Kung et al., 2023). At the same time, AI may also augment knowledge work by improving efficiency, accuracy, and speed for analytical, programming, or writing tasks (Dell'Acqua et al., 2023; Eloundou et al., 2023; Noy \& Zhang, 2023), while driving demand for new skill sets (Bessen, 2016). Studies further

document higher demand or valuation for skills that complement AI (Alekseeva et al., 2021; Stephany \& Teutloff, 2024). Such complementarities are explored by, for instance, measuring skill co-occurrences in job requirements (Anderson, 2017) or tracking how knowledge clusters shape workforce polarisation (Alabdulkareem et al., 2018). These findings emphasise that skills and technology are interlinked through intricate interdependencies (Dibiaggio et al., 2014; Neffke, 2019).

Complementation and substitution can manifest in two ways: popularity (demand) and valuation (wages). Skills may remain in demand but experience devaluation, or they may become less common while retaining high wage premiums. For example, seminal research links wage differentials to skill-biased technological change (Goldin \& Katz, 2007a), and computerisation has been shown to increase wage inequality (Bessen, 2016). It is likely both substitution and complementation coexist, meaning AI can diminish demand for some skills while raising demand for others (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2018b; Autor et al., 2003). As Acemoglu et al. succinctly put it:
"...if different tasks require different skills, then the adoption of AI technologies may also change the set of skills that exposed establishments demand (and list in their vacancies). Skills relevant for tasks now performed by algorithms will be demanded less frequently, and new skills necessary for working alongside AI algorithms may also start being included in vacancies" (Acemoglu et al., 2021, p.8)

# Unresolved Questions in AI's Skill Impacts 

Scholars have highlighted two key shortcomings in the existing literature. First, although the studies cited here adhere to rigorous research standards, much of the broader discourse-including media coverage-relies on theoretical models, expert opinions, and predictions whose assumptions may not be validated or widely accepted (Yilmaz et al., 2023). Numerous works seeking to forecast substitution effects of AI (e.g., Agrawal et al., 2019; Webb, 2019) produce widely varying estimates. This can introduce bias for at least two reasons: there is no shared expert consensus on whether AI complements or substitutes human skills (Brynjolfsson \& Mitchell, 2017; Frank et

al., 2019), and experts often underestimate the diverse skill sets within occupations, leading to potential over- or underestimations (Arntz et al., 2016). Gathering empirical evidence to test and refine hypotheses is notably difficult. As Frank et al. (2019, p.6531) observe, "major barriers that inhibit scientists from measuring the effects of AI on the future of work ... include the lack of high-quality data about the nature of work ... [and] lack of empirically informed models of key microlevel processes."

Second, there is little agreement on which skills AI excels at and the labour market outcomes that result, fuelling debates about which tasks, occupations, and skill sets are affected, to what extent, and how (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2018b; Autor et al., 2003; Brynjolfsson \& Mitchell, 2017). The strongest evidence suggests a complex interplay of both substitution and complementarity: skills replicable by AI may face diminishing demand, while those critical for working alongside AI see rising demand (Acemoglu et al., 2021).

Building on previous research linking technology adoption to shifts in skill demands (Acemoglu et al., 2021), and mindful of the aforementioned limitations, this paper seeks to enhance understanding of this emerging field. Specifically, we investigate whether growing demand for AI-centric work not only reshapes skill requirements within AI-intensive roles but also exerts broader influence on related labour markets. More concretely, we ask: Does increasing AI demand boost both the demand and valuation of AI-complementary skills-within AI-focused positions and across neighbouring occupations, industries, and regions?

# Hypotheses 

The growing integration of AI into economic activity profoundly affects labour market skill requirements. We conceptualise these shifts through "internal" and "external" effects:

1. Internal effects operate within AI-intensive roles, requiring new bundles of skills directly tied to AI tasks.
2. External effects spill over into the broader workforce-affecting other workers within the same occupation, competing firms in an industry, and entire regions-even when those workers do not directly engage with AI.

# Internal Effects 

In roles that directly interact with AI (e.g., data scientists, machine learning engineers), increasingly complex and opaque models demand stronger ethical reasoning to mitigate biases and unintended consequences, greater emphasis on algorithmic accountability, and higher levels of digital literacy and adaptability. Economically, these changes reflect cross-derivative complementarities in the worker's personal "production function," where one skill (e.g., ethics) becomes more valuable when another (e.g., AI technical proficiency) gains importance. As AI-based tasks proliferate, the positive cross-partial derivatives indicate that AI skills enhance returns to complementary non-technical skills.

## External Effects at the Occupation, Industry, and Regional Levels

Outside AI-specific roles, skill demands evolve through spillover effects. At the occupational level, workers who do not directly interface with AI may still require basic digital literacy or familiarity with AI outputs to interpret and act on insights generated by colleagues. At the industry level, competitive pressures from AI-adopting firms can push other companies to invest in raising their overall technical proficiency, as well as soft skills-like teamwork, resilience, and ethics-that facilitate rapid, responsible responses to AI-driven changes. At the regional level, AI hubs (e.g., in autonomous driving or AI-led recruitment) can shift local labour market dynamics, encouraging broader digital upskilling and awareness of AI's ethical and social implications. Conceptually, these spillovers reflect positive cross-partial derivatives at the firm and regional levels, where an AI-intensive environment raises the marginal value of digital, teamwork, resilience, and ethics skills across diverse roles.

To capture both "within-role" and "beyond-role" dimensions of AI's labour market impact, we propose:

## Internal Effects (Within AI Roles)

- H1a: Roles requiring AI skills also exhibit higher demand for AI-complementary skills.
- H1b: Complementary skills in AI-intensive roles command higher wages.

- H1c: Roles requiring AI skills show reduced demand for skills considered substitutable by AI.

# External Effects (Spillover Beyond AI Roles) 

- H2a: In regions, industries, or occupations with high AI adoption, non-AI roles will exhibit increased demand for complementary skills.
- H2b: In these same contexts, non-AI roles will show decreased demand for substitute skills.

By integrating both "within-role" and "beyond-role" perspectives, this framework aims to illuminate how technological change affects immediate job requirements while reshaping the broader ecosystem of talent and expertise.

# Methods and Data
## Data

Following prior work, we assume that employers' online vacancy postings reflect evolving skill demands and valuations (Acemoglu et al., 2021; Deming \& Noray, 2020). We leverage a dataset of approximately 12 million $(\mathrm{n}=11,729,662)$ U.S. online job postings from January 2018 to December 2023, created by Lightcast and provided by the Burning Glass Institute (BGI). These postings are scraped from over 65,000 websites-including job boards, company career pages, and aggregators (Lightcast Data, n.d.)—capturing the "near-universe" of online vacancies (Acemoglu et al., 2021, p.1). Each posting contains information such as job title, occupation category, salary, and a detailed skill list derived from the text.

Lightcast data have previously facilitated studies on technology's labour market effects (e.g., Alekseeva et al., 2021; Acemoglu et al., 2021; Ehlinger \& Stephany, 2023; Hazell \& Taska, 2020; Babina et al., 2024; Hershbein \& Kahn, 2018). Extensive tests confirm that Lightcast data mirror U.S. vacancy trends from JOLTS and the BLS, and the dataset aligns closely with state-level BLS statistics (see Appendix Tables 1-2). Although there is some overrepresentation of professional and technical occupations relative to blue-collar jobs-an established characteristic of online postings data (Carnevale et al., 2014)—our focus on knowledge work and comparative skill shares minimises any potential biases. On average, the dataset differs from official BLS figures by only $3 \%$.

## Defining Skills

To classify complementary and substitutable skills, we consulted the literature (e.g., Autor et al., 2003; Acemoglu \& Autor, 2011; Frey \& Osborne, 2017; Wirtz et al., 2018; Felten et al., 2019; Frank et al., 2019). This review yielded five "substitutable" skill clusters-Basic Data Skills, Summary and Reporting, Language and Text Review, Customer Service, and Office and Financial Administration-and seven "complementary" skill clusters-Analytical Thinking, Digital Literacy, Resilience and Agility, Technical Proficiency, Ethics, Self-Efficiency, and Working

With Others (see Appendix Table 3). Mapping individual skills from the Lightcast database to these clusters produced 18 skills for the five substitutable clusters (Appendix Table 4) and 71 for the seven complementary clusters (Appendix Table 5).

We labelled a posting as demanding substitutable or complementary skills if it required at least one skill from the relevant lists. This binary threshold ensures we capture important skills with minimal sample loss, particularly for smaller clusters (e.g., "customer service," "ethical standards and conduct"). Higher thresholds (e.g., two or more complementary or substitutable skills) would exclude a large proportion of postings and lead to incomplete analysis (see Appendix Figures 1-2).

# Defining AI roles 

Following a skills-based approach (Acemoglu \& Autor, 2011; Alekseeva et al., 2021; Ehlinger \& Stephany, 2023), we identified AI-related roles by the presence of at least one AI skill requirement in the job posting. This method avoids misclassifying non-AI positions within AI-focused firms (e.g., a Human Resources Manager at an AI company) as AI roles.

First, we created a classification of AI skills—labelled "AI User" or "AI Creator" (115 skills) by building on an existing classification provided by BGI and then refined each skill's subcategory in line with established definitions (Russell \& Norvig, 2016; Squicciarini \& Nachtigall, 2021). Skills with unclear or broad descriptions were verified by listing the occupations demanding them at the SOC_5 level, ensuring correct classification (e.g., "ChatGPT" was reclassified as an NLP AI User skill after analysis showed it was mostly used by writers and editors). The final scheme includes eight AI skill categories (see Appendix Table 6):

1. Machine Learning Creators
2. Natural Language Processing (NLP) Creators
3. AI Development and Operations
4. Computer Vision and Image Processing
5. Prediction and Analytics
6. Machine Learning Users
7. NLP Users

# 8. AI Applications and Tools 

As with complementary and substitutable skills, we labelled a posting as AI-related if it required at least one AI skill. This threshold minimises sample loss (see Appendix Figure 3) and aligns with prior research (Ehlinger \& Stephany, 2023; Squicciarini \& Nachtigall, 2021). More information on measures and variables can be found in the Appendix.

## Methods
## 2018-2023 comparison

We begin by conducting a time series analysis to observe how skill demand and salaries evolve. First, we compare demand for complementary and substitutable skills in AI roles against non-AI roles from 2018 to 2023. We restrict the sample to knowledge work occupations, allowing for a more relevant comparison than if we included blue-collar or agricultural jobs, which seldom require skills like office administration or technical proficiency. For the start and end year of our sample, we calculate the share of postings (in AI vs. non-AI roles) requiring complementary or substitutable skills. Next, we repeat this approach for salary, comparing log-transformed salary in AI roles demanding complementary or substitutable skills with those in non-AI roles.

## Regression models

Regression as a method of analysis has an established precedent of being used to understand the relationships between artificial intelligence and patterns in demand and wages in the labour market (e.g. Acemoglu et al., 2021; Stephany \& Teutloff, 2024). In this paper, we employ logistic regression to understand the associations between AI roles and demand for complementary and substitutable skills, and linear regression to understand if demand for complementary and substitutable skills is associated with higher or lower salaries in AI occupations (internal effects), as well as in the external effects analysis. A range of control variables are accounted for, which

are presented in the table below, along with their justification based on literature review.

In this study, logistic regression (Maximum Likelihood Estimation, MLE method) is used to understand the association between demand for complementary or substitutable skills (dependent variables) and AI roles (independent variable). Motivated by the theoretical precedent detailed in the section above, various controls are introduced. Model 1 controls for individual factors (education and experience levels) and Model 2 controls for job-related and structural factors (full-time employment, knowledge work occupation, skill variety level, high GDP state, year). Model 3 includes all control variables along with the independent variable of interest. Models 1-3 are fitted both for the complementary skills model and the substitute skills model. The regression formula is captured as follows:

$$
\log \left(\frac{p}{1-p}\right)=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}(\text { Is an AI job })+\text { Controls }
$$

Where:

- p is the probability of demand for skills
- $\beta_{0}$ is the intercept
- $\beta_{1}$ represents the effect of a job being an AI role
- "Controls" represents a collective term for all other control variables included to adjust for confounding factors, which for Model 3 include minimum years of experience, minimum education level, knowledge work occupation, full-time employment, skill variety level, high GDP state, and year indicators (2019, 2020, 2021, 2022, 2023)

To complete our analysis of internal effects, we use linear regression (Ordinary Least Squares, OLS method) to understand the association between (log-transformed) salary for AI roles (dependent variable) and demand for complementary or substitutable skills (independent variables). Motivated by the theoretical precedent detailed in the section above, various controls are introduced. Model 1 controls for

individual factors (education and experience levels) and Model 2 controls for job-related and structural factors (full-time employment, knowledge work occupation, company size, skill variety level, high GDP state, year). Model 3 includes all control variables along with the independent variable of interest. Models 1-3 are fitted both for the complementary skills model and the substitute skills model. The regression formula is captured as follows:

For substitutable skills:

$$
\log \text { _salary }=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}(\text { Demand for Substitutable Skills })+\text { Controls }+\epsilon
$$

For complementary skills:

$$
\log \text { _salary }=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}(\text { Demand for Complementary Skills })+\text { Controls }+\epsilon
$$

Where:

- log_salary is the natural logarithm of the salary for AI roles
- $\beta_{0}$ is the intercept
- $\beta_{1}$ represents the coefficient for "Demand for Substitutable Skills" or "Demand for Complementary Skills"
- "Controls" is a collective term for all other control variables in the model, which for Model 3 include minimum years of experience, minimum education level, knowledge work occupation, company size (Fortune 500 company or not), full-time employment, skill variety level, high GDP state, and year indicators (2019, 2020, 2021, 2022, 2023)
- $\varepsilon$ (epsilon) is the error term, which captures the variability in log_salary not explained by the model

An additional control variable is included in the salary regressions (Fortune 500 company) owing to the need to adjust for the fact that the largest companies are likely to pay the highest salaries (Brown \& Medoff, 1989). Company names in the job

postings data set were first directly matched to Fortune 500 company names. However, company names are not always consistently written. For example, management consulting company McKinsey \& Company appears in the data as "mckinsey", "mckinsey \& co inc united states", and "mckinsey \& company, inc. united states". Consequently, we employed a fuzzy match using the FuzzyWuzzy package, which uses Levenshtein Distance to calculate the differences between sequences (Cohen, 2020). ${ }^{1}$

Finally, we turn our attention to measuring external effects. We use linear regression (Ordinary Least Squares, OLS method) to understand the association between the penetration of AI (as measured by prevalence of AI role postings) and their external effects on the demand for complementary and substitutable skills also in non-AI roles, at the occupation, industry, and regional levels. For each of our six regressions, we aggregate data by the relevant category - occupation, industry, or region - and year, excluding those with fewer than ten AI role postings per year to ensure robust results. To linearise relationships, log transformations were applied to all variables. We control for the total number of postings and postings for the converse skill category (i.e. complementary skills in substitutable regression, substitutable skills in complementary regression) to ensure that the observed effects of AI role postings are not confounded by broader variations in labour demand (e.g., market size fluctuations) and account for structural dynamics of skill ecosystems/interactions within the labour market.

The regression equation is expressed as:

$$
\ln \left(y_{i, k}\right)=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1} \ln \left(X_{1, i, k}\right)+\beta_{2} \ln \left(X_{2, i, k}\right)+\beta_{3} \ln \left(X_{3, i, k}\right)+\epsilon_{i, k}
$$

Where:

- $\mathrm{y}_{\mathrm{i}, \mathrm{k}}$ is the dependent variable (Complementary Non-AI roles or Substitutable Non-AI roles) by year i and level k (occupation/industry/region)
- $\mathrm{X}_{1, \mathrm{i}, \mathrm{k}}$ is total Postings (log-transformed)
- $\mathrm{X}_{2, \mathrm{i}, \mathrm{k}}$ is AI Postings (log-transformed)

# Comparative descriptive statistics analysis: 

First, we employ comparative descriptive statistics to examine differences in demand for specific complementary skills in AI compared to non-AI roles, and for complementary skills in AI user jobs compared to AI creator jobs, visualised in simple line charts. Second, motivated by these nuanced findings, we further examine the differential demand for specific complementary or substitutable skills clusters between specific AI role categories compared to non-AI roles, with results visualised using a heatmap. In addition, motivated by recent findings (e.g., McKinsey, 2023; World Economic Forum, 2023) suggesting a recent major step change in AI adoption, specifically the use of (generative) AI to substitute and complement knowledge work, we further investigate the change in demand for complementary and substitutable skills clusters across AI role categories over time, from 2018-2022 to 2023.

In the second part of the analysis, we investigate the compensation of complementary or substitutable skills within various AI role categories. We begin by transforming the salary variable by taking its natural logarithm, resulting in a new variable, 'log_salary,' to address skewness. Next, we calculate the median log salary for each AI role category, and compare this to the median log salary for each AI role category with each complementary or substitutable skills cluster. The results were again visualised using a heatmap to easily depict the magnitude and direction of findings.

Finally, for the comparisons detailed above, we run statistical significance tests to ensure our observed results are statistically significant. For demand comparisons we employ a two-sided two-proportion Z-test for those comparisons fulfilling the test condition that each group should have at least 10 successes and 10 failures. The hypotheses are as follows:
$\mathrm{H}_{0}: \mathrm{P}_{\mathrm{AI}}=\mathrm{P}_{\text {non-AI }}$, the proportion of AI roles that require a specific skill is equal to the proportion of non-AI roles that require that skill
$\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{A}}: \mathrm{P}_{\mathrm{AI}} \neq \mathrm{P}_{\text {non-AI }}$, the proportions are not equal

For a small number of comparisons ( $\mathrm{n}=2$ for the complementary skills analysis and $\mathrm{n}=5$ for the substitutable skills analysis) not fulfilling the test conditions, we use Fisher's Exact test, which is particularly useful for small sample sizes and is used to test the equivalence or difference between two proportions (Heumann et al., 2016).

For the salary analyses we employ a two-sided Mann-Whitney U test to check for statistical significance in differences, with the following hypotheses:
$\mathrm{H}_{0}$ : The distributions of both groups are equal, there is no difference in the medians of the two groups
$\mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{A}}$ : The distributions of the two groups are not the same, there is a difference in the medians of the two groups

For a number of comparisons ( $\mathrm{n}=20$ for the complementary skills analysis and $\mathrm{n}=21$ for the substitutable skills analysis) not fulfilling the condition of $\mathrm{n}>=30$, we use Mood's median test, which has good efficiency for smaller sample sizes (G. W. Brown \& Mood, 1951). For all tests, results are considered statistically significant at $\mathrm{p}<0.05$.

# Findings
## Part A: Internal Effects

In this section, we compare how complementary and substitute (substitutable) skills manifest in AI versus non-AI roles. Complementary skills-such as digital literacy, analytical thinking, ethics, or technical proficiency-either enable creating and/or using AI systems or are augmented by AI tools to increase collective effectiveness (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2018a; Autor, 2015). Substitutable skills refer to tasks or abilities that AI systems can perform with little or no human intervention, often routine or rule-based tasks, including basic data processing, text synthesis, and grammar (Frey \& Osborne, 2017). The U.S. Bureau of Labour Statistics (BLS) projects that while office, administrative, sales, design, and legal occupations may see reduced labour demand due to AI substitution, computer and mathematical occupations-where most AI roles lie-will be among the fastest-growing through 2033 (BLS, 2024c).

Against this backdrop, we identify a notable rise in demand for AI-complementary skills, accompanied by an increasing wage premium for such skills within AI roles. By contrast, substitutable skills have diminished in both prevalence and value. We also find that certain complementary skills-especially analytical thinking, resilience, agility, and technical proficiency-are doubly in demand and offer higher earnings, creating a "compounding effect."

## Prevalence and Value of Complementary and Substitute Skills

We first provide a baseline by comparing the share and salary of AI and non-AI roles that demand complementary or substitutable skills (Figure I). Demand for complementary skills is proportionally higher in AI roles than in non-AI roles and, conversely, substitutable skills appear at lower rates in AI roles. Notably, the gap in complementary skills demand widens between AI and non-AI roles over time (2020-2023), while the gap in substitutable skills demand narrows ${ }^{3}$. As shown in the

Being an AI role is associated with about a 0.91 percentage-point increase in complementary skills intensity.

Figure 1. AI roles increasingly emphasize complementary skills-commanding higher salaries-while demand for substitutable skills declines, thereby narrowing its gap. Meanwhile, this trend widens the overall demand gap between AI and non-AI roles for complementary skills, as substitutable skills lose value across both segments.

Our regression models (Table II) show that complementary skills are more prevalent among AI roles, regardless of other confounders. In the full model (Model 6, pseudo R² $=0.43$ ), the coefficient for "Is an AI role" is $0.195(\mathrm{p}<0.01)$, implying a $22 \%$ higher likelihood that a posting will demand complementary skills after controlling for individual, job, and structural factors. For substitutable skills we observe the opposite pattern. In the full model (Model 3), the coefficient for "Is an AI role" is -0.427 ( $\mathrm{p}<$ 0.01 ), indicating a $34.8 \%$ lower likelihood of substitutable skills demand for AI roles, when adjusting for controls.

Table 8: Jobs that require AI skills are more likely to include complementary skill requirements, indicating that AI adoption correlates with greater emphasis on these supportive capabilities. Conversely, AI-related positions display a lower likelihood of including substitutable skill requirements, suggesting that as AI becomes more prevalent, reliance on easily automated skills diminishes.

![table_2](table_2)

We next examine how the wages of AI roles are affected by complementary and substitute skills. Demand for substitutable skills shows a strong, consistent link to lower AI-role salaries across all model specifications (Table III). In Model 3 (adjusted $\mathrm{R}^{2}=0.32, \mathrm{~F}=156.3, \mathrm{p}=0.0$ ), substitutable skills have a coefficient of $-0.085(\mathrm{p}<$ 0.01 ), implying an $8.2 \%$ lower salary, controlling for other factors. Surprisingly, we also find a significant but smaller negative effect of complementary skills on AI-role salaries. In Model 6 (adjusted $\mathrm{R}^{2}=0.31, \mathrm{~F}=153.2, \mathrm{p}=0.0$ ), the coefficient is $-0.042(\mathrm{p}<0.01)$, translating to a $4.1 \%$ lower salary for AI positions requiring complementary skills, after controls. Potential interpretations of this result are discussed in the Discussion chapter.

Table III: In AI-intensive positions, the presence of substitutable skills aligns with reduced salary levels, reflecting a pay penalty for roles emphasizing easily automated tasks. However, even though complementary skills are in higher demand for AI jobs, their presence does not consistently translate into wage premiums, suggesting a complex relationship between skill composition and compensation.

# Granular Analysis 

We turn our focus to a granular analysis of complementary skills. First, we compare the odds of finding demand for specific complementary skills in AI roles compared to non-AI roles (Figure II). We make three observations. First, the comparatively higher importance of Analytical Thinking, Technical Proficiency and Resilience and Agility in AI roles; second, the growing technicality of AI roles, as reflected in the increasing odds ratio for Technical Proficiency skills since 2020; and

finally, the thus-far neglected but growing comparative importance of Ethics skills in $\mathrm{AI}^{4}$.
![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

Figure II: Certain complementary skills-like analytical thinking and technical proficiency-are notably more common in AI roles than in non-AI roles, signaling a reshaping of skill priorities in technology-driven fields.

Motivated by these nuances, we delve deeper into skill complementarities, focusing on which AI role-complementary skill combinations are especially prevalent (Figure III). We compare each AI role category's demand for a complementary skill cluster against its baseline demand in non-AI roles. The heatmap reveals higher demand for most complementary skills-particularly analytical thinking, resilience and agility, technical proficiency, self-efficiency, and teamwork-across AI roles. Two exceptions, ethics and digital literacy, might reflect the still under emphasized role of ethics in AI or an implicit assumption of digital literacy in these jobs.

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{4}$ We also examine whether comparative demand for complementary skills (compared to non-AI roles) differs between different kinds of AI roles, namely between AI user jobs (jobs with skills like e.g., 'ChatGPT', 'Sentiment Analysis', 'Applications Of Artificial Intelligence') and AI creator jobs (jobs with skills like e.g., 'Large Language Modeling', 'Topic Modeling', 'Word2Vec Models'). We observe, interestingly, that while comparative demand for complementary skills is higher for AI creator jobs at the beginning of our observation period, AI user jobs have caught up to the level of AI creator jobs, even exceeding these levels in 2020 and 2022.

Although consistency is generally high across AI role categories, variations do emerge. For instance, machine learning jobs show strong complementarity with technical proficiency but not ethics. Statistical tests (two-proportion Z-tests or Fisher's exact test) confirm that most ( 41 out of 56 ) of these differences are significant. A brief qualitative text analysis of AI job postings mentioning the word "complement(ing)" $(\mathrm{n}=263)$ supports these findings: employers highlight the importance of working in cross-functional teams, translating technical solutions into business requirements, maintaining a "growth mindset," and combining data analytics with human intuition.

Substitutable skills show notably lower demand in AI roles, particularly for basic data skills, summary and reporting, customer service, and office and financial administration. Demand appears relatively consistent across different AI role categories, suggesting similar patterns for both AI creators and AI users. Again, statistical tests confirm the significance of most observed differences ( 51 out of 56 ). Interestingly, skills often viewed as automatable-such as information management, prediction, or decision-making-are actually more in demand in all AI role categories than in non-AI roles, underscoring the gap between theoretical assumptions and practical realities.

![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)

Figure III: Across various AI role categories, complementary skills such as analytical thinking and resilience tend to appear more frequently than in non-AI roles, while ethics and digital literacy remain comparatively underrepresented.

To explore compensation within specific AI role categories and substitutable skill clusters, we compare median log salaries for postings demanding these skills against the median for the broader AI category (e.g., machine learning creators). Most AI roles requiring substitutable skills exhibit lower median salaries, with a few minor exceptions (e.g., AI development/operations needing customer service), but follow-up Mann-Whitney U or Mood's median tests indicate these exceptions are not statistically significant.

Figure IV further illustrates how much more prevalent certain complementary skills are for AI roles. Individual skills, such as Resilience and Agility or Analytical Thinking are significantly more prevalent among AI roles. When turning to skill

combinations we observe that the likelihood of observing them among AI roles increases significantly ${ }^{5}$.
![img-3.jpeg](img-3.jpeg)

Figure IV Left: Select individual complementary skills have higher odds of being demanded in AI jobs, suggesting particularly sought after AI-complementary capabilities in the labor market. Right: Select pairs of complementary skills have higher odds of being demanded in AI jobs, hinting at particularly sought after combinations of technical and supportive capabilities in the labor market.

# 4. The case of Data Scientists 

Finally, to shed light on a real-life occupation, we turn to a detailed analysis of Data Scientists, including coefficient plots to assess the compounding impact of complementary skills on wages. We find that for Data Scientists, we find higher odds of observing analytical thinking ( $89 \%$ higher), technical proficiency ( $41 \%$ higher), resilience and agility ( $36 \%$ higher), digital literacy ( $18 \%$ higher), self-efficiency ( $13 \%$ higher) and teamworking skills ( $7 \%$ higher), and lower odds of demand for ethics skills ( $44 \%$ lower), echoing our findings for AI jobs overall (Figure V left). We further note that for working with others and digital literacy this effect is greater than for other AI jobs, perhaps reflecting the broader stakeholder interactions common to data scientist roles. Moreover, we also find that these resilience and agility skills and ethics skills are associated with $4 \%$ and $8 \%$ higher salary, respectively (Figure V right). Notably, we observe that for resilience and agility skills, this salary premium is higher than for both

[^0]:    ${ }^{5}$ Examining AI role-complementary skill combinations shows that certain groups benefit from a modest salary premium, though only two-(prediction and analytics with technical proficiency, and machine learning user roles requiring resilience and agility)-are statistically significant (see Appendix Figure 13). Overall, the data suggest strong overall demand for complementary skills in AI roles, even if only specific skill clusters yield notable wage premiums.

other AI roles and non-AI roles, underscoring the high perceived value of this skill in the rapidly-evolving data science profession.
![img-4.jpeg](img-4.jpeg)

Figure V Left: Data Scientist roles display notably higher odds of demanding resilience, agility, self-efficiency, and ethics, demonstrating how AI-driven occupations increasingly seek versatile human attributes. Right: Among Data Scientist positions, certain complementary skills correlate with modest increases in wages, indicating that these attributes can enhance the economic value of data-centric expertise.

# Part B: External Effects 

In the second half of this paper, we examine external effects across the broader economy, showing that AI influences both complementary and substitutable skills even outside AI-specific roles. We hypothesise that rising AI adoption (i.e., a higher prevalence of AI roles) within an occupation, industry, or region increases the demand for complementary skills and decreases the need for substitutable skills-even in non-AI positions. For instance, as AI becomes more integral to autonomous vehicle technology, urban planners may be in higher demand to design cities optimised for self-driving systems, while traditional roles like traffic signal maintenance could decline as AI-driven traffic management negates the need for physical signal infrastructure.

Our findings support this hypothesis at the occupational, industry, and regional levels (Table IV and Figure VI). Growth in AI roles has a positive effect on roles demanding complementary skills. A $1 \%$ increase in AI postings corresponds to a $0.054 \%$ rise in complementary non-AI postings ( $\mathrm{p}<0.05$ ). Thus, a doubling of AI postings - such as occurred from 2018 to 2023 - aligns with a $5.4 \%$ increase in complementary non-AI roles at the industry level. Conversely, a $1 \%$ increase in AI postings correlates with a $0.019 \%$ decline in substitutable non-AI postings ( $1.9 \%$ for a doubling), although this result is not statistically significant ( $\mathrm{p}=0.51$ ). Over time, growth in AI roles is linked to a higher number of non-AI roles demanding

complementary skills and a lower number requiring substitutable skills. Doubling AI postings increases complementary non-AI postings by $2.8 \%$ ( $\mathrm{p}<0.05$ ) and lowers substitutable non-AI postings by $2.4 \%$ ( $\mathrm{p}=0.30$ ).

Similar trends emerge regionally. Doubling AI postings raises complementary non-AI postings by $3.0 \%$ ( $\mathrm{p}<0.05$ ) and reduces substitutable non-AI postings by $5.77 \%$ ( $\mathrm{p}<0.05$ ). Replicating these analyses in the UK ( $\mathrm{n}=10,003,732$ ) and Australia ( $\mathrm{n}=5,001,726$ ) yields similar results (Table IV). Applying these findings to real BLS job vacancy data from 2018-2023 (BLS, 2024) suggests a yearly gain of 51,113 jobs and a loss of 34,612 jobs, netting 16,501 new non-computing jobs annually.

The influence of AI adoption is more pronounced at the industry and regional levels than at the occupational level. For example, as AI becomes more prevalent in automotive manufacturing, marketing and maintenance workers must also understand AI use cases (e.g., technical proficiency, ethics). Regionally, increased AI postings in Silicon Valley could boost roles in legal compliance (AI regulations) and education (AI training programmes). It is less likely that a spike in AI-focused HR Assistant roles in one firm would raise complementary skill demand in other companies' HR Assistant positions.

Overall, we link the rise in AI roles to an annual net job increase of 287,593 for 2018-2023, accounting for growth in non-AI complementary roles, fewer non-AI substitutable roles, and more AI roles. # Discussion 

In this paper, we present empirical evidence for both substitution and complementation effects driven by artificial intelligence (AI), observable in skill demand and compensation. Crucially, these effects occur not only within AI-focused jobs but also beyond them-across different occupations, industries, and regions. By examining AI's impact at a granular, skills-based level and drawing on real-world job postings data, this research offers a more precise view of AI's influence on the labour market than broader occupation-level analyses or forecasting studies reliant on expert opinion or theoretical models.

## Internal Effects
## Demand

Our regression results indicate a positive association between AI roles and demand for complementary skills, alongside a negative association between AI roles and demand for substitutable skills. This finding provides preliminary evidence that AI adoption not only complements certain knowledge-worker skills, elevating their demand, but also substitutes others, thereby lowering their demand. Although these results do not establish causality, they guide future research directions and underscore the strategic importance of workforce planning and skill development for policymakers, organisations, and individuals. The data further show that job postings requiring AI technologies have proportionally higher demand for complementary knowledge-worker skills and proportionally lower demand for substitutable skills, which is noteworthy given that non-AI roles already exhibit a strong baseline demand for complementary skills (close to $70 \%$ ). Taken together, the observation that AI creation or usage coincides with co-occurring complementation and substitution supports the need for policy interventions such as structured reskilling initiatives, transitional programmes, and potential adjustments in social security systems to address wage compression or worker displacement. These patterns also highlight the importance of curricular reforms to incorporate analytical, digital, and interpersonal competencies that prepare

future employees for AI-augmented roles, especially where human-AI collaboration drives productivity and innovation.

In addition, our findings point to three further contributions. First, they suggest that particularly strong complementarities exist at a granular level. Examples include technical proficiency in machine learning creation, natural language processing creation, and computer vision and image processing jobs ( $84-247 \%$ higher demand, p $<0.05$ ), or digital literacy in data-intensive AI development and operations ( $33 \%$ higher, $\mathrm{p}<0.05$ ), and resilience and agility in rapidly evolving machine learning user roles ( $92 \%$ higher, $\mathrm{p}<0.05$ ). Conversely, the data also reveal particularly strong substitution effects, such as basic data skills in roles using AI applications and tools $(-86 \%, \mathrm{p}<0.05)$, or summary and reporting in NLP jobs, which commonly involve generative technologies like ChatGPT ( $-78 \%, \mathrm{p}<0.05$ ). Identifying these strong complementarities in specific technical skill sets highlights areas for strategic investment, while pinpointing strong substitution effects reveals where automation poses the greatest risk.

Second, the findings reflect recent shifts in demand, notably the growing emphasis on ethics skills across many AI role categories, which may indicate a broader societal and regulatory move toward responsible AI development and deployment.

Third, the results show that while AI creator roles have consistently required higher levels of complementary skills, AI user roles have been slower to adopt these skills but eventually caught up and, by 2022, reached parity with AI creator roles. This signals a maturation of AI technologies: as they become embedded in everyday workflows, even non-technical roles need to develop AI-complementary capabilities. Organisations and policymakers must therefore invest in education and training to expand access to these skills across the broader labour market.

# Valuation of skills 

Assuming that complementation and substitution effects manifest in how skills are both demanded and valued, we turned to examine worker compensation. Overall, our findings support the idea that vacancies for AI-related jobs requiring substitutable skills tend to have lower salaries than AI jobs without such requirements, but they do

not indicate any wage premium associated with complementary skills. Regression results reveal small negative salary effects linked to both complementary and substitutable skills (approximately $-8 \%$ and $-4 \%$, respectively), underscoring the complex nature of wage determination in an environment shaped by technological change.

Further investigation of substitutable skills shows that the wage penalty is highest $(7-8 \%, \mathrm{p}<0.05)$ for basic data skills, customer service, and office and financial administration skills in computer vision and image processing roles. This pattern may reflect broader wage compression resulting from technological advances (Acemoglu \& Restrepo, 2018a). As routine tasks-such as basic data processing, summarising and reporting, and office or financial administration-become automated, workers in roles dependent on these skills may face downward pressure on wages due to diminished demand and reduced bargaining power.

Conversely, a few complementary skill sets exhibit small wage gains in certain AI contexts, such as technical proficiency in prediction and analytics roles or resilience and agility in machine learning user jobs (each around $+1 \%, \mathrm{p}<0.01$ ). However, on the whole, our results do not show a clear wage premium for complementary skills in AI roles, contrasting with assertions that tech workers' social and collaborative skills should command higher pay (Edinger, 2013). While complementary skills remain in high demand for AI positions, their direct influence on salary may be tempered by broader economic forces and employer-specific factors. Future research could investigate this nuanced link between skill complementarity and wages to inform strategies for equitable compensation in AI-driven workplaces.

# External Effects 

Finally, our findings show that AI adoption generates substantial external effects at the occupational, industry, and regional levels. Growth in AI roles corresponds with increased demand for non-AI complementary roles and a decline in non-AI substitutable roles. This pattern appears across all three levels of analysis but is most pronounced regionally, where doubling AI roles is associated with a statistically significant $3.0 \%$ rise in non-AI complementary roles and a $5.8 \%$ decline in

non-AI substitutable roles, and at the industry level, where doubling AI roles correlates with a $5.4 \%$ increase in non-AI complementary roles. Notably, the complementarity effect exceeds the substitution effect, and the size of these effects varies by industry. In Management and Business Operations and Computer and Mathematical Occupations, for instance, more than 1.5 and 1.7 complementary roles, respectively, are gained for each substitutable role lost.

To our knowledge, these results are among the first to quantify the external spillovers linked to AI adoption. They suggest that labour markets are being subtly reshaped as demand shifts toward complementary skills even outside direct AI roles, challenging narratives of net displacement and highlighting the nuanced impact of AI on the workforce.

The implications of these findings are multifaceted. For individuals, they underscore the importance of acquiring AI-complementary skills-such as technical proficiency, analytical thinking, and ethical frameworks-to navigate emerging labour market demands. For companies, the results emphasise the need for proactive workforce planning and reskilling investments. For policymakers, regional spillover effects point to the importance of targeted education and workforce development in high-AI-adoption areas, alongside safety nets and incentives to mitigate local disparities for displaced workers.

# Limitations 

Finally, this study faces several limitations. First, as noted by Acemoglu et al. (2021) and Carnevale et al. (2014), online vacancy postings tend to overrepresent professional and technical occupations relative to blue-collar jobs. Moreover, the data exclude alternative hiring channels, such as headhunting, offline advertisements, external contractors, or in-house upskilling (Ehlinger \& Stephany, 2023).

Second, skills requirements in postings may not perfectly reflect the actual skills used after hire. For instance, an employee's skill usage might shift in response to market conditions or organisational changes. While we focus on demand and compensation at the point of recruitment, readers should keep these possible post-hire

changes in mind. A robust organisational-behaviour literature (e.g., Mullins, 2007) addresses these dynamics in more depth.

Third, we assume that higher posted salaries indicate the perceived market value of particular skills, even though actual wages can diverge from advertised rates. Still, these postings represent employers' willingness to pay at the recruitment stage and are thus pertinent for this study's focus on valuation (Ehlinger \& Stephany, 2023).

Fourth, when working with large datasets, even small effects can seem statistically significant. We ran 1,000 demand regressions on 1,000 random samples (each $\mathrm{n}=10,000$ ) to check robustness. Coefficients for complementary skills ranged from about -1.0 to 1.5 (mean $=0.217$, close to the main result of 0.195 ), whereas substitutable skills ranged from -2.5 to 0.5 (mean $=-0.492$, close to -0.427 ). P-values spanned 0.0 to 1.0. However, AI roles remain relatively scarce $(47,871)$ compared to the entire sample $(11,729,662)$. In smaller samples of 10,000 postings, only a few AI roles may appear, making significant results less likely. This scarcity motivates using a large dataset. By combining regression with descriptive analysis and smaller sub-cluster studies, we aimed to mitigate this limitation. We also applied cautious interpretation, emphasising real-world relevance.

Fifth, these findings do not establish causality. Yet by identifying associations and patterns among variables, they contribute to the broader debate on how the labour market is evolving under technological change. Future experimental or longitudinal studies may clarify the causal mechanisms suggested here.

Lastly, our dataset primarily covers United States job postings. Since technology's labour market effects differ across countries (Arntz et al., 2016), these findings may not fully generalise elsewhere. Additional research should explore regional differences to provide a fuller picture.

# Conclusion 

This study aimed to expand our understanding of AI's internal and external effects on knowledge-worker skills-specifically, how AI complements certain competencies (e.g., technology literacy, ethics, analytical thinking) while potentially

substituting others (e.g., basic data tasks, office and financial administration). Following Acemoglu et al. (2021) and Deming and Noray (2020), we relied on job postings-employers' "footprints" indicating evolving skill demands and wage offers-to analyse around 12 million online vacancies.

Our work illuminates the relationship between AI creation/usage and the complementarity or substitution of knowledge-worker skills, yielding five key contributions. First, we find that AI roles are positively associated with demand for complementary skills and negatively associated with demand for substitutable skills. Second, job postings that include AI requirements display proportionally more requests for complementary skills and fewer requests for substitutable skills compared to non-AI postings. Third, we identify powerful complementarities between particular AI roles and clusters of complementary skills, as well as strong substitution effects for certain AI roles and substitutable skills-most notably an increasing emphasis on ethics across many AI categories. Fourth, we show that AI jobs demanding substitutable skills carry lower salaries than AI jobs without such requirements; basic data skills, customer service, and office/financial administration skills in computer vision and image processing roles suffer the highest wage penalty. However, we find no evidence of a wage premium for complementary skills. Finally, we uncover external complementation effects: as AI roles grow, the number of non-AI roles that demand complementary skills also rises. Crucially, the complementarity effect exceeds the substitution effect.

Future research directions include extending our analysis to other regions (e.g., Europe and Asia) to capture potential geographic variations, employing qualitative methods (such as interviews with recruitment managers) to explore perceptions of skill demand and valuation, and pursuing experimental or longitudinal studies to establish causality. As debates on the benefits and risks of "AI at work" (Brynjolfsson et al., 2023) persist, researchers, policymakers, employers, and job-seekers all stand to benefit from an empirically grounded understanding of these influential effects.

# Appendix
## Appendix Details on Data and Methods
## Measures and variables
## Demand for skills

Because there are relatively few AI roles $(\mathrm{n}=47,871)$ compared to non-AI roles ( $\mathrm{n}=11,681,791$ ), skill demand is expressed as the proportion (share) of postings requiring a particular skill rather than an absolute count. Using Python, we define a custom function that calculates this share by dividing the number of job postings mentioning skill S by the total number of job postings in category C (for example, a specific AI role category) and expressing the result as a percentage.

$$
\text { Demand for Skill }=\frac{\text { Number of Jobs Requiring } S}{\text { Total Number of Jobs in } C} \times 100
$$

## Percentage Growth / Percentage Difference

To compare relative changes in demand or salary between two groups or time periods, we create a custom percentage growth (also used for comparative percentage difference) function. The percentage growth/difference is calculated using the following formula:

$$
\text { Percentage Difference }=\frac{\left(V_{2}-V_{1}\right)}{V_{1}} \times 100
$$

where V1 and V2 are the initial and final values, respectively.

## Log-transformed salary

Salary data can be skewed, which could affect the results of statistical analyses. Therefore, before undertaking our salary analyses, we conducted some tests to validate if the salary variable requires transformation before its use in the analysis. A visual

inspection of a histogram and Q-Q plot (see Appendix Figure 4) showed that the distribution of salary is right-skewed and the Q-Q plot is deviated from the line. Thus, to stabilise the variance, making it more suitable for my analysis, we log-transform (natural logarithm) the salary variable.

Lastly, we estimate the real-world impact of these findings, measuring external effects with the following formula:

$$
\text { Effect }=(\text { AI Jobs } \times(\exp (\text { coefficient } \cdot \ln (\text { AI Jobs }))-1)) \times \text { Multiplier }
$$

Where:

- Coefficient refers to the relevant regression coefficient, as follows:
o Occupation Level: $\beta_{\text {complementary }}=0.0282, \beta_{\text {substitutable }}=-0.0237$
o Industry Level: $\beta_{\text {complementary }}=0.0541, \beta_{\text {substitutable }}=-0.0191$
o Regional Level: $\beta$ complementary $=0.042, \beta_{\text {substitutable }}=-0.0447$
- The Multiplier adjusts the effects computed using our OJV data to a real-word estimate using BLS data:

$$
\text { Multiplier }=\frac{\text { BLS Industry Size }}{\text { Number of Rows in the Dataset for Occupation }}
$$

abstract:
This paper examines whether artificial intelligence (AI) acts as a substitute
or complement to human labour, drawing on 12 million online job vacancies from
the United States spanning 2018-2023. We adopt a two-pronged approach: first,
analysing "internal effects" within roles explicitly requiring AI, and second,
investigating "external effects" that arise when industries, occupations, and
regions experience increases in AI demand. Our focus centres on whether
complementary skills-such as digital literacy, teamwork, resilience, agility,
or analytical thinking-become more prevalent and valuable as AI adoption grows.
Results show that AI-focused roles are nearly twice as likely to require skills
like resilience, agility, or analytical thinking compared to non-AI roles.
Furthermore, these skills command a significant wage premium; data scientists,
for instance, are offered 5-10% higher salaries if they also possess resilience
or ethics capabilities. We observe positive spillover effects: a doubling of
AI-specific demand across industries correlates with a 5% increase in demand
for complementary skills, even outside AI-related roles. Conversely, tasks
vulnerable to AI substitution, such as basic data skills or translation,
exhibit modest declines in demand. However, the external effect is clearly net
positive: Complementary effects are up to 1.7x larger than substitution
effects. These results are consistent across economies, including the United
Kingdom and Australia. Our findings highlight the necessity of reskilling
workers in areas where human expertise remains increasingly valuable and
ensuring workers can effectively complement and leverage emerging AI
technologies.
